short description|broad category of electronic music
Electronic dance music (EDM), also known as dance music, club music, or simply dance,<ref name="Koskoff_44">harvp|Koskoff|2004|p=44</ref> is a broad range of percussive electronic music genres made largely for nightclubs, raves and List of electronic dance music festivals|festivals. It is generally Record producer|produced for gapless playback|playback by disc jockeys who create seamless selections of tracks, called a DJ mix|mix by segueing from one recording to another.<ref>harvp|Butler|2006|pp=12–13, 94</ref> EDM producers also perform their music live in a concert or festival setting in what is sometimes called a live PA. In Europe, EDM is more commonly called 'dance music', or simply 'dance'.<ref name=Definition>cite web|title=Definition |url = http://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/british/dance-music?q=dance+music|website=Dictionary.cambridge.org|accessdate=2017-07-09</ref>

In the late 1980s and early 1990s, following the emergence of Rave music|raving, pirate radios and an upsurge of interest in club culture, EDM achieved widespread mainstream popularity in Europe. In the United States at that time, acceptance of dance culture was not universal; although both Electro (music)|electro and Chicago house music were influential both in Europe and the United States, mainstream media outlets and the record industry remained openly hostile to it.There was also a perceived association between EDM and drug culture, which led governments at state and city level to enact laws and policies intended to halt the spread of rave culture.<ref name=guardian-conquered />

Subsequently, in the new millennium, the popularity of EDM increased globally, largely in Australia and the United States. By the early 2010s, the term "electronic dance music" and the initialism "EDM" was being Push–pull strategy#Push–pull music marketing future|pushed by the American music industry and Music journalism|music press in an effort to rebranding|rebrand American rave culture.<ref name=guardian-conquered/> Despite the industry's attempt to create a specific EDM brand, the initialism remains in use as an umbrella term for multiple genres, including house music|house, techno, trance music|trance, drum and bass, and dubstep, as well as their respective subgenres.<ref>Cite news|url=https://midniteblaster.com/2018/07/09/what-is-edm-music/|title=What is EDM music? - Midnite Blaster|date=2018-07-09|work=Midnite Blaster|access-date=2018-09-03|language=en-US</ref><ref name=noisey-realgenre>cite web|title=Is EDM a Real Genre?|url=http://noisey.vice.com/en_ca/blog/is-edm-a-real-genre|website=Noisey|publisher=Vice|accessdate=25 February 2015</ref><ref>RA Roundtable: EDM in AmericaResident Advisor. [http://www.residentadvisor.net/feature.aspx?1709 "RA Roundtable: EDM in America"]. N. p., 2012. Web. 18 May. 2014.</ref><ref>[http://www.factmag.com/2013/07/10/the-fact-dictionary-how-dubstep-juke-cloud-rap-and-many-more-got-their-names/6/ "The FACT Dictionary: How 'Dubstep', 'Juke', 'Cloud Rap' and Many More Got Their Names'"], ''FACT Mag'', July 10, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://dailytrojan.com/2014/03/03/hardstyle-musics-growing-influence/ "Hardstyle music’s growing influence"] ''Dailytrojan'', Web. Mar 3, 2014.</ref>

History
See also|Electronic music|History of DJing
Various EDM genres have evolved over the last 40 years, for example; electro, techno, house, trance, drum and bass etc. <!--Editors, please don't expand this section in an effort to describe every genre. The point is not to provide a genre guide, but to refer people to the "list of electronic music genres" page, and to briefly cover the relationship between the genres and "EDM".-->Stylistic variation within an established EDM genre can lead to the emergence of what is called a subgenre. Hybridization, where elements of two or more genres are combined, can lead to the emergence of an entirely new genre of EDM.<ref name="genres">cite journal|date=2001|title=Genres, Subgenres, Sub-Subgenres and More: Musical and Social Difference Within Electronic/Dance Music Communities|url=http://ir.uiowa.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1001&context=commstud_pubs|format=PDF|journal=Journal of Popular Music Studies|volume=13|pages=59–75|doi=10.1111/j.1533-1598.2001.tb00013.x|author=Kembrew McLeod</ref>

=Precursors in the 1960s and 1970s=
See also|P-Funk
In the late 1960s bands such as Silver Apples created electronic music that was intended to be danced to.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xReSZczxSsU]</ref> Other early examples of music that influenced later electronic dance music include Jamaican dub music in the 1970s,<ref name="armada">[https://www.armadamusic.com/edm-electronic-dance-music EDM – ELECTRONIC DANCE MUSIC], Armada Music</ref> the synthesizer-based disco music of Italian producer Giorgio Moroder in the late 1970s, and the electro-pop of Kraftwerk and Yellow Magic Orchestra in the mid to late 1970s.<ref>Richard James Burgess (2014), ''The History of Music Production'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=qMKiAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA115 page 115], Oxford University Press</ref>

Dub
Main|Dub music
See also|Sound system (Jamaican)|Deejay (Jamaican)
Listen
|filename     = King_Tubby_Meets_Rockers_Uptown_(song).ogg
|title        = "King Tubby Meets Rockers Uptown"
|description  = Augustus Pablo's "King Tubby Meets Rockers Uptown (song)|King Tubby Meets Rockers Uptown" (1974), an example of dub music.<ref>cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/king-tubbys-meets-rockers-uptown-r103916 |title=King Tubby's Meets Rockers Uptown – Augustus Pablo |date= |work=Allmusic |publisher=Rovi Corporation |accessdate=2011-05-31</ref>

Author Michael Veal considers dub music, a Jamaican music stemming from roots reggae and Sound system (Jamaican)|sound system culture that flourished between 1968 and 1985, to be one of the important precursors to contemporary electronic dance music.<ref name="veal"/> Dub productions were #Remixing in Electronic music|remixed reggae tracks that emphasized rhythm, fragmented lyrical and melodic elements, and reverberant textures.<ref>Michael Veal (2013), [https://books.google.com/books?id=kYtiAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA85 ''Dub: Soundscapes and Shattered Songs in Jamaican Reggae'', pages 85–86], Wesleyan University Press</ref> The music was pioneered by studio engineers, such as Sylvan Morris, King Tubby, Errol Thompson (audio engineer)|Errol Thompson, Lee "Scratch" Perry, and Scientist (musician)|Scientist.<ref name="veal">Michael Veal (2013), [https://books.google.com/books?id=kYtiAgAAQBAJ&pg=PP54 ''Dub: Soundscapes and Shattered Songs in Jamaican Reggae'', pages 26–44, "Electronic Music in Jamaica"], Wesleyan University Press</ref> Their productions included forms of tape editing and sound processing that Veal considers comparable to techniques used in ''musique concrète''. Dub producers made improvised deconstructions of existing Multitrack recording|multi-track reggae mixes by using the studio mixing board as a performance instrument. They also foregrounded spatial effects such as Reverberation unit|reverb and Delay (audio effect)|delay by using Mixing console#Auxiliary send routing|auxiliary send routings creatively.<ref name="veal"/>

Despite the limited electronic equipment available to dub pioneers such as King Tubby and Lee "Scratch" Perry, their experiments in remix culture were musically cutting-edge.<ref name="cambridge20">Nicholas Collins, Margaret Schedel, Scott Wilson (2013), [https://books.google.com/books?id=bQeAtG97BmEC&pg=PA20 ''Electronic Music: Cambridge Introductions to Music'', page 20], Cambridge University Press</ref> Ambient dub was pioneered by King Tubby and other Jamaican sound artists, using DJ-inspired Ambient music|ambient electronics, complete with drop-outs, echo, equalization and Psychedelic music|psychedelic electronic effects. It featured layering techniques and incorporated elements of world music, deep bass lines and harmonic sounds.<ref name="eem">cite book |title=Electronic and Experimental Music: Technology, Music, and Culture |last=Holmes |first=Thom |year=2008 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0203929599 |page=403 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hCthQ-bec-QC |accessdate=1 April 2013</ref> Techniques such as a long echo delay were also used.<ref>cite book|last1=Toop|first1=David|title=Ocean of Sound|date=1995|publisher=Serpent's Tail|isbn=9781852423827|page=115</ref>

Hip hop
Main|Hip hop music
See also|Rapping|Turntablism
listen
|filename=Rapper's Delight sample.ogg
|title="Rapper's Delight"
|description=30 second sample of "Rapper's Delight" from ''Sugarhill Gang (album)|Sugarhill Gang''
|filetype=Ogg
Hip hop music has played a key role in the development of electronic dance music since the 1970s.citation needed|date=May 2017 Inspired by Jamaican sound system culture Jamaican-American DJ Kool Herc introduced large bass heavy speaker rigs to the Bronx.<ref name="places">Arthur P. Molella, Anna Karvellas (2015),[https://books.google.com/books?id=FyDaCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA47 "Places of Invention,"] Smithsonian Institution, p.47.</ref> His parties are credited with having kick-started the New York City|New York hip-hop movement in 1973.<ref name="places"/>  A technique developed by DJ Kool Herc that became popular in hip hop|hip hop culture was playing two copies of the same record on two turntables, in alternation, and at the point where a track featured a break (music)|break. This technique was further used to manually loop (music)|loop a purely percussive break, leading to what was later called a Break (music)#Break beat (element of music)|break beat.<ref>Nicholas Collins, Margaret Schedel, Scott Wilson (2013), [https://books.google.com/books?id=bQeAtG97BmEC&pg=PA105 ''Electronic Music: Cambridge Introductions to Music'', page 105], Cambridge University Press</ref> In the 1980s and 1990s hip-hop DJs used turntables as musical instruments in their own right and virtuosic use developed into a creative practice called turntablism.<ref name="wired">[https://www.wired.com/2002/05/blackbox/ Six Machines That Changed The Music World], ''Wired (magazine)|Wired'', May 2002</ref>

Disco
Main|Disco
See also|Euro disco|Italo disco|Hi-NRG

In 1974, George McCrae's early disco hit "Rock Your Baby" was one of the first records to use a drum machine,<ref>Martin Russ (2012), [https://books.google.com/books?id=X9h5AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA83 ''Sound Synthesis and Sampling'', page 83], CRC Press</ref> an early Roland Corporation|Roland rhythm machine.<ref name="books.google.co.uk">Mike Collins (2014), [https://books.google.com/books?id=tdEABAAAQBAJ&pg=PA320 ''In the Box Music Production: Advanced Tools and Techniques for Pro Tools'', page 320], CRC Press</ref> Its use of a drum machine was anticipated by Sly and the Family Stone's "Family Affair (Sly and the Family Stone song)|Family Affair" (1971), which anticipated the sound of disco, with its rhythm echoed in "Rock Your Baby".<ref name="echols21">Alice Echols (2010), [https://books.google.com/books?id=DzrvOAA2tvAC&pg=PA21 ''Hot Stuff: Disco and the Remaking of American Culture'', page 21], W. W. Norton & Company</ref> The use of drum machines in "Family Affair"<ref name="echols21"/> and Timmy Thomas' "Why Can't We Live Together" (1972),<ref name="echols250">Alice Echols (2010), [https://books.google.com/books?id=DzrvOAA2tvAC&pg=PA250 ''Hot Stuff: Disco and the Remaking of American Culture'', page 250], W. W. Norton & Company</ref> which used a 1972 Roland rhythm machine,<ref name="books.google.co.uk"/> influenced the adoption of drum machines by later disco artists.<ref name="echols21"/><ref name="echols250"/> Disco producer Biddu used synthesizers in several disco songs from 1976 to 1977, including "Bionic Boogie" from ''Rain Forest'' (1976),<ref name="bionic_boogie">Discogs release|2809569|Biddu Orchestra – Bionic Boogie</ref> "Soul Coaxing" (1977),<ref name="soal_coaxing">Discogs release|874902|Biddu Orchestra – Soul Coaxing</ref> and ''Eastern Man'' and ''Futuristic Journey''<ref name="cduniverse">cite web|title=Futuristic Journey And Eastern Man CD|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?pid=7735242|publisher=CD Universe|accessdate=7 July 2011</ref><ref name="discogs_futuristic">Discogs master|109852|Biddu Orchestra – Futuristic Journey|type=album</ref> (recorded from 1976 to 1977).<ref>allmusic|album|r1401917|Futuristic Journey and Eastern Man</ref>

Listen
|filename = Donna Summer I Feel Love.ogg
|title = Donna Summer: "I Feel Love" (1977)
|description = Donna Summer's "I Feel Love" (1977), produced by Giorgio Moroder, was a seminal Euro disco song.

European acts Silver Convention, Love & Kisses|Love and Kisses, Munich Machine, and American acts Donna Summer and the Village People were acts that defined the late 1970s Euro disco sound. In 1977, Giorgio Moroder and Pete Bellotte produced "I Feel Love" for Donna Summer. It became the first well-known disco hit to have a completely synthesised backing track. Other disco producers, most famously American producer Tom Moulton, grabbed ideas and techniques from dub music (which came with the increased Jamaican migration to New York City in the seventies) to provide alternatives to the four on the floor style that dominated.<ref name="Billboard.com">cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/search/charts?page=41&f&#91;0&#93;=ts_chart_artistname%3A*donna%20summer*&f&#91;1&#93;=ss_bb_type%3Achart_item&type=2&artist=donna%20summer|title=Chart Search: Billboard|work=billboard.com</ref><ref>cite book
| last =Shapiro
| first =Peter
| title =Modulations: A History of Electronic Music
| publisher =Caipirinha Productions, Inc.
|year=2000
| location =
| pages =254 pages
| isbn =978-0-8195-6498-6  see p.45, 46</ref> During the early 1980s, the popularity of disco music sharply declined in the United States, abandoned by major US record labels and producers. Euro disco continued evolving within the broad mainstream pop music scene.<ref>cite news|title=ARTS IN AMERICA; Here's to Disco, It Never Could Say Goodbye|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/10/arts/arts-in-america-here-s-to-disco-it-never-could-say-goodbye.html?pagewanted=3&src=pm|newspaper=The New York Times|date=10 December 2002</ref>

Synth-pop
Main|Synth-pop
See also|Electropop|Minimal wave
listen
|filename=Trans-Europe Express sample.ogg
|title="Trans-Europe Express"
|description=Kraftwerk's "Trans-Europe Express" from the 1977 album ''Trans-Europe Express (album)|Trans-Europe Express''
|filetype=Ogg
|filename2=YMO - Firecracker.ogg
|title2="Firecracker"
|description2=Yellow Magic Orchestra's "Firecracker" from 1978. It was later sampled by artists such as Afrika Bambaata and Jennifer Lopez.
Synth-pop (short for 'synthesizer pop';sfn|Trynka|Bacon|1996|p=60 also called 'techno-pop')<ref name="SR">cite journal|title=unknown|journal=Stereo Review|date=1983|volume=48|page=89|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QVkJAQAAMAAJ&q=%22technopop%22+%22synthpop%22&dq=%22technopop%22+%22synthpop%22</ref><ref name="electrosynth">harvnb|Collins|Schedel|Wilson|2013|p=97|loc="synth pop (also called electro pop, techno pop, and the like)"; harvnb|Hoffmann|2004|p=2153|loc="Techno-pop, also termed synth-pop or electro-pop"</ref> is a subgenre of new wave music<ref>allmusic|subgenre|synth-pop-ma0000002887|Synth Pop</ref> that first became prominent in the late 1970s and features the synthesizer as the dominant musical instrument. It was prefigured in the 1960s and early 1970s by the use of synthesizers in progressive rock, electronic music|electronic, art rock, disco, and particularly the "Krautrock" of bands like Kraftwerk. It arose as a distinct genre in Japan and the United Kingdom in the post-punk era as part of the New wave music|new wave movement of the late 1970s to the mid-1980s.

Early synth-pop pioneers included Japanese group Yellow Magic Orchestra, and British bands Ultravox, the Human League and Berlin BlondesCitation needed|reason=This claim needs a reliable source; proof needed that they are regarded as pioneers.|date=May 2018. the Human League used monophonic synthesizers to produce music with a simple and austere sound. After the breakthrough of Gary Numan in the UK Singles Chart in 1979, large numbers of artists began to enjoy success with a synthesizer-based sound in the early 1980s, including late-1970s debutants like Japan (band)|Japan and Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark, and newcomers such as Depeche Mode and Eurythmics. In Japan, Yellow Magic Orchestra's success opened the way for synth-pop bands such as P-Model, Plastics (band)|Plastics, and Hikashu. The development of inexpensive polyphonic synthesizers, the definition of MIDI and the use of Dance music|dance beats, led to a more commercial and accessible sound for synth-pop. This, its adoption by the style-conscious acts from the New Romantic movement, together with the rise of MTV, led to success for large numbers of British synth-pop acts (including Duran Duran and Spandau Ballet) in the United States.

=Dance music in the 1980s=
See also|New school hip hop|Miami bass|Freestyle music|Hip house|Latin house|Industrial dance music

Post-disco
Main|Post-disco
See also|Boogie (genre)
Listen
|filename=Let's Groove by Earth, Wind & Fire.ogg
|title="Let's Groove"
|description=Earth, Wind & Fire's "Let's Groove" (1981), an example of post-disco music.<ref name="VH1">cite web|first= Ben |last= Smith |title= Meghan Trainor Helps Count Down 10 Songs That Are All About That Bass |publisher= VH1|VH1 Music. Viacom Media Networks |date= August 20, 2014 |url= http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2014-08-20/10-songs-that-are-all-about-that-bass/ |accessdate= October 27, 2014 |quote= This post-disco pop funk epic is centered on a relentless, repeating bassline that really does make you want to, uh, groove.</ref>

During the post-disco era that followed the backlash against "disco" which began in the mid to late 1979, which in the United States lead to civil unrest and a riot in Chicago known as the Disco Demolition Night,<sup>Electronic dance music#cite note-shadow-13|[13]</sup> an underground movement of "stripped-down" disco inspired music featuring "radically different sounds"<sup>Electronic dance music#cite note-AMG1-14|[14]</sup> started to emerge on the East Coast of the United States|East Coast.<sup>Electronic dance music#cite note-Kellmann-15|[15]Electronic dance music#cite note-18|[Note 1]</sup> This new scene was seen primarily in the New York metropolitan area and was initially led by the urban contemporary artists that were responding to the over-commercialisation and subsequent demise of disco culture. The sound that emerged originated from P-Funk<sup>Electronic dance music#cite note-Parliament-19|[18]</sup> the electronic side of disco, dub music, and other genres. Much of the music produced during this time was, like disco, catering to a Gramophone record|singles-driven market.<sup>Electronic dance music#cite note-AMG1-14|[14]</sup> At this time creative control started shifting to independent record companies, less established producers, and club DJs.<sup>Electronic dance music#cite note-AMG1-14|[14]</sup> Other dance styles that began to become popular during the post-disco era include dance-pop,<sup>Electronic dance music#cite note-Slant-20|[19]Electronic dance music#cite note-21|[20]</sup> Boogie (genre)|boogie,<sup>Electronic dance music#cite note-AMG1-14|[14]</sup> Electro (music)|electro, Hi-NRG, Italo disco, House music|house,<sup>Electronic dance music#cite note-Slant-20|[19]Electronic dance music#cite note-22|[21]Electronic dance music#cite note-DancingMachines-23|[22]Electronic dance music#cite note-24|[23]</sup> and techno.<sup>Electronic dance music#cite note-DancingMachines-23|[22]Electronic dance music#cite note-25|[24]Electronic dance music#cite note-26|[25]Electronic dance music#cite note-27|[26]Electronic dance music#cite note-28|[27]</sup>

Electro
Main|Electro (music)
File:Roland TR-808 drum machine.jpg|thumb|left|200px|The instrument that provided electro's synthesized programmed drum beats, the Roland TR-808 drum machine.
Listen
|filename=Planet Rock (song).ogg
|title="Planet Rock"
|description="Planet Rock (song)|Planet Rock" (1982), by Afrika Bambaataa and Soulsonic Force, a seminal Electro (music)|electro song, utilizing a Roland Corporation|Roland TR-808.<ref name="wire_1996"/>

In the early 1980s, electro (short for "electro-funk") emerged as a fusion of Synthpop|electro-pop, funk, and Boogie (genre)|boogie. Also called electro-funk or electro-boogie, but later shortened to electro, cited pioneers include Ryuichi Sakamoto, Afrika Bambaataa,<ref name="wire_1996">citation|title=The Wire, Volumes 143–148|work=The Wire (magazine)|The Wire|year=1996|page=21|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qtw4AQAAIAAJ|accessdate=2011-05-25 (see [http://www.thewire.co.uk/in-writing/essays/a-z-of-electro online link])</ref> Zapp (band)|Zapp,<ref>cite journal|title=Zapp|date=August 1999|journal=Vibe (magazine)|Vibe|volume=6|page=84</ref> D Train (music group)|D.Train,<ref name=ElectroHistoryRoots>cite web|url=http://www.electrofunkroots.co.uk/articles/what.html|title=Electro-Funk > WHAT DID IT ALL MEAN ?|publisher=Greg Wilson on electrofunkroots.co.uk|accessdate=2009-12-23</ref> and Sinnamon.<ref name=ElectroHistoryRoots/> Early hip hop and rap combined with German and Japanese electropop influences such as Kraftwerk and Yellow Magic Orchestra inspired the birth of electro.<ref name="Electro">cite web|title=Electro|publisher=Allmusic|url=http://www.allmusic.com/style/electro-ma0000002571|accessdate=2012-06-20</ref> As the electronic sound developed, instruments such as the bass guitar and drumset|drums were replaced by synthesizers and most notably by iconic drum machines, particularly the Roland TR-808. Early uses of the TR-808 include several Yellow Magic Orchestra tracks in 1980–1981, the 1982 track "Planet Rock (song)|Planet Rock" by Afrika Bambaataa, and the 1982 song "Sexual Healing" by Marvin Gaye.<ref>cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/music/story/2008/11/27/f-history-of-the-808.html |title=Slaves to the rhythm |accessdate=2008-11-28 |work=CBC News |date=November 28, 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201041939/http://www.cbc.ca/arts/music/story/2008/11/27/f-history-of-the-808.html |archivedate=December 1, 2008 </ref> In 1982, producer Arthur Baker (musician)|Arthur Baker, with Afrika Bambaataa, released the seminal "Planet Rock (song)|Planet Rock", which was influenced by Yellow Magic Orchestra, used Kraftwerk samples, and had drum beats supplied by the TR-808. Planet Rock was followed later that year by another breakthrough electro record, "Nunk" by Warp 9. In 1983, Hashim Music|Hashim created an electro-funk sound with "Al-Naafyish (The Soul)"<ref name="wire_1996"/> that influenced Herbie Hancock, resulting in his hit single "Rockit (song)|Rockit" the same year. The early 1980s were electro's mainstream peak. According to author Steve Taylor,<ref name="The A to X of alternative music">cite book|last1=Taylor|first1=Steve|title=The A to X of alternative music|date=2004|publisher=Continuum|location=London|isbn=9780826482174|page=25|edition=2nd ed., reprint|url=https://books.google.com/?id=KPOsu8JOHO8C&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=electro-funk+1st+dance+music+genre#v=onepage&q=electro-funk%201st%20dance%20music%20genre&f=false</ref>
Afrika Bambaataa's  Planet Rock serves as a "template for all interesting dance music since".<ref name="The A to X of alternative music"/>

House music
Main|House music
See also|Chicago house|Garage house|Deep house
Listen
| filename   = Jesse Saunders - On and On.ogg
| title       = Jesse Saunders – "On and On" (1984)
| description = "On and On" (1984) by Jesse Saunders, often cited as the 'first' house music|house record. Features the Roland TB-303|TB-303, Roland TR-808|TR-808, Korg Poly-61 and sampling (music)|sampled bassline from Player One's "Space Invaders (Player One song)|Space Invaders" (1979).
| pos         = right
| filename2    = Mr Fingers - Can You Feel It.ogg
| title2        = Mr. Fingers: "Can You Feel It?" (1986)
| description2  = "Can You Feel It? (Larry Heard song)|Can You Feel It?" (1986) by Fingers, Inc.|Mr. Fingers (Larry Heard). It was a seminal deep house track.
| pos2         = right

In the early 1980s, Chicago radio jocks The Hot Mix 5 and club DJs Ron Hardy and Frankie Knuckles played various styles of dance music, including older disco records (mostly Philly soul|Philly disco and Salsoul Records|Salsoul<ref name=Slslpop>Cite book|title=Popular Music Genres: An Introduction|last1=Roy|first1=Ron|last2=Borthwick|first2=Stuart|page=255|isbn=9780748617456|year=2004|publisher=Edinburgh University Press</ref> tracks), electro music|electro funk tracks by artists such as Afrika Bambaataa,<ref name="Vincent">cite book|author=Rickey Vincent|title=Funk: The Music, The People, and The Rhythm of The One|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tb-FBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA289|year=2014|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-1-4668-8452-6|page=289</ref> newer Italo disco, B-boying|B-Boy hip hop music by Man Parrish, Jellybean Benitez, Arthur Baker (musician)|Arthur Baker, and John Robie, and Electropop|electronic pop music by Kraftwerk and Yellow Magic Orchestra. Some made and played their own edits of their favorite songs on reel-to-reel tape, and sometimes mixed in effects, drum machines, and other rhythmic electronic instrumentation. The hypnotic electronic dance song "On and On", produced in 1984 by Chicago DJ Jesse Saunders and co-written by Vince Lawrence, had elements that became staples of the early house sound, such as the Roland TB-303 bass synthesizer and minimal vocals as well as a Roland Corporation|Roland (specifically Roland TR-808|TR-808) drum machine and Korg (specifically Korg Poly-61|Poly-61) synthesizer.

"On and On" is sometimes cited as the 'first house record',<ref>Mitchell, Euan. [http://www.4clubbers.net/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=125 Interviews: Marshall Jefferson] 4clubbers.net dead link|date=September 2016|bot=mediccbignore|bot=medic</ref><ref>cite web |url=http://www.flyglobalmusic.com/fly/archives/uscanada_features/finding_jesse_-.html |title=Finding Jesse – The Discovery of Jesse Saunders As the Founder of House |date=2004-10-25 |website=Fly Global Music Culture |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322041641/http://www.flyglobalmusic.com/fly/archives/uscanada_features/finding_jesse_-.html |archivedate=2012-03-22 |accessdate=2012-08-14</ref> though other examples from around that time, such as Steve "Silk" Hurley|J.M. Silk's "Music Is the Key (Steve "Silk" Hurley song)|Music is the Key" (1985), have also been cited.<ref>cite journal|journal=Dance Music Report|date=1989-12-16|title=Back To Basics|last=Paoletta|first=Michael|page=12</ref> House music quickly spread to other American cities such as Detroit, New York City, and Newark—all of which developed their own regional scenes. In the mid-to-late 1980s, house music became popular in Europe as well as major cities in South America, and Australia.<ref name=unesco_4>cite journal | url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0012/001201/120152e.pdf | title=The club DJ: a brief history of a cultural icon | date=July–August 2000 | last=Fikentscher | first=Kai | journal=UNESCO Courier | page=47 | quote=Around 1986/7, after the initial explosion of house music in Chicago, it became clear that the major recording companies and media institutions were reluctant to market this genre of music, associated with gay African Americans, on a mainstream level. House artists turned to Europe, chiefly London but also cities such as Amsterdam, Berlin, Manchester, Milan, Zurich, and Tel Aviv.&nbsp;... A third axis leads to Japan where, since the late 1980s, New York club DJs have had the opportunity to play guest-spots.</ref> Chicago House experienced some commercial success in Europe with releases such as "House Nation" by House Master Boyz and the Rude Boy of House (1987). Following this, a number of house inspired releases such as "Pump Up the Volume (song)|Pump Up The Volume" by MARRS|MpipeApipeRpipeRpipeS (1987), "Theme from S'Express" by S'Express (1988), and "Doctorin' the House" by Coldcut (1988) entered the pop charts.

Techno, acid house, rave
Main|Techno|Acid house
See also|Detroit techno|Electronic body music|Balearic house|Second Summer of Love
Listen
